  "explanation": "In determining the appropriate sentence, the court must weigh both the severity of the crime and the mitigating circumstances. The defendant committed a serious breach of fiduciary duty by embezzling $25,000 from their employer. White-collar crimes of this nature inflict financial harm and damage trust in professional environments, requiring a penalty that provides general deterrence. However, there are significant mitigating factors in this case. The defendant has no prior criminal record, indicating this is an isolated lapse in judgment rather than a pattern of criminal behavior. Furthermore, the defendant has already begun making restitution, demonstrating remorse and a willingness to make the victim whole. Balancing the need for punitive consequences with the defendant's rehabilitative potential and ongoing restitution efforts, a brief period of incarceration is warranted to impress the gravity of the offense, which will be followed by a period of probation to ensure full repayment of the stolen funds.",
  "verdict": 6
